  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with grilled versus braised beef?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled beef develops charred, smoky flavors that pair beautifully with bold, structured wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Malbec, which can match the intensity and complement the char. Braised beef, with its tender texture and rich, complex sauce, works better with medium to full-bodied wines like Côtes du Rhône or Barolo that have good acidity to cut through the richness. The cooking method fundamentally changes the flavor profile and requires different wine characteristics for optimal pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine at the same temperature regardless of the beef cut?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">No, the beef cut and preparation should influence your serving temperature. Lean cuts like filet mignon pair well with lighter reds served slightly cooler (60-62°F) to preserve elegance, while fatty cuts like ribeye benefit from fuller-bodied wines served at cellar temperature (62-65°F) to balance the richness. For aged steaks, serve premium wines at proper cellar temperature to showcase their complexity against the beef's concentrated flavors.</p>
  </div>

