    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I use the same wine for cooking beef and serving with the meal?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely, and it's often recommended for flavor harmony. When cooking with wine, the alcohol evaporates but the wine's fundamental flavors concentrate and integrate with the beef, creating a seamless pairing when you serve the same wine alongside. However, avoid using your most expensive bottle for cooking – a good quality, moderately-priced wine that you'd enjoy drinking works perfectly for both purposes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget-friendly wine that works with most beef dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Côtes du Rhône offers exceptional versatility and value for beef pairings, typically under $15-20. These blends provide medium to full body, balanced acidity, and complementary earthy flavors that work with everything from burgers to pot roast. Spanish Tempranillo from regions like Campo de Borja or Jumilla also delivers excellent beef-friendly characteristics at budget prices, with good structure and food-friendly tannins.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is it wrong to pair white wine with beef?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Not at all – the key is matching the weight and intensity of both the wine and beef preparation. Full-bodied, oak-aged Chardonnay pairs beautifully with lighter beef preparations like carpaccio or beef tartare. Rich, textured whites like white Rhône blends or aged Rioja Blanco can complement beef dishes with cream sauces or lighter cooking methods where the beef isn't the dominant flavor component.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How far in advance should I open wine before serving with beef?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young, tannic reds benefit from 1-2 hours of decanting before serving with beef to soften harsh tannins and allow the wine to integrate better with the meat's richness. Older wines (10+ years) should only be opened 30-60 minutes before serving to prevent over-oxidation. Medium-bodied wines like Pinot Noir or Chianti need minimal decanting – just 15-30 minutes to open up their aromatics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with beef?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing wine based solely on the protein rather than considering the entire dish, especially the sauce and seasonings. A filet mignon with béarnaise sauce needs a different wine than the same cut with a peppercorn crust or mushroom sauce. The accompaniments, cooking method, and seasonings often have more impact on the pairing than the beef cut itself, so always consider the complete flavor profile of your dish.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are wine and beef pairings good for beginners to wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, beef and wine pairings are excellent for beginners because beef's rich, savory flavors provide a forgiving backdrop that complements most red wines. The umami and fat in beef help soften wine tannins, making even bold wines more approachable. Start with classic combinations like Cabernet Sauvignon with steak or Merlot with beef stew – these time-tested pairings demonstrate fundamental pairing principles while being nearly foolproof for new wine drinkers.</p>
  </div>
